**\\n\\nI’m considering whether I can fetch something externally right now. I need to check if I should add dependencies in build.gradle since the POM has an HTTP repo, which might get blocked. I'm thinking Maven Central might not have all the old Gradle artifacts either. It seems there are issues with the ProGuard task execution and compatibility with certain methods. I wonder if it's possible to adjust the test execution and configuration effectively without the protected API calls. Let’s see what options I have!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing ProGuard compatibility**\\n\\nI need to decide if I should remove proguard() because of binary incompatibility with Gradle 9. If I'm using gradleTestKit, I'm wondering if the task's getLogging could be causing a NoSuchMethodError due to a bytecode descriptor mismatch. Maybe the current DefaultTask has a bridge for internal methods? I’m considering creating a subclass of ProGuardTask to override getLogging, but I need to confirm how method resolution works and how it impacts method dispatch. It’s a complex situation!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Deciding on ProGuard execution**\\n\\nI'm realizing that if the subclass defines a method, it won't be found during resolution because it's not actually recognized as a subclass of ProGuardTask. So, I can't rely on that. Using an older version of Gradle seems like an option, but it brings its own issues. It might be better to remove the ProGuard execution altogether. I wonder if I could test if proguard() throws NoSuchMethod, but that doesn't seem meaningful. I think it's best to avoid that call entirely.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_deERqUjNQznAqS3YtXRp8D9w|fc_0b261ae36c6e8a600169fe02f4f8e881969b680f55a81aa062", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/net.sf.proguard/proguard-gradle/5.2.1/src/test/java/net_sf_proguard/proguard_gradle/Proguard_gradleTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "    @Test\n    void executesProGuardForASmall